{"cursor":"22354","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn linguistics, 'word order typology' refers to the study of the order of the\nsyntactic constituents of a language, and how different languages can employ\ndifferent orders. Correlations between orders found in different syntactic\nsubdomains are also of interest. The primary word orders that are of interest\nare the constituent order of a clause â the relative order of subject, object,\nand verb; the order of modifiers (adjectives, numerals, demonstratives,\npossessives, and adjuncts) in a noun phrase; and the order of adverbials.\n\nSome languages use relatively restrictive word order, often relying on the order\nof constituents to convey important grammatical information. Othersâoften those\nthat convey grammatical information through inflectionâallow more flexibility,\nwhich can be used to encode pragmatic information such as topicalisation or\nfocus. Most languages, however, have a preferred word order. Comrie, 1981\n\nMost nominativeâaccusative languagesâwhich have a major word class of nouns and\nclauses that include subject and objectâdefine constituent word order in terms\nof the finite verb (V) and its arguments, the subject (S), and object\n(O). Hengeveld, Kees (1992). Non-verbal predication. Berlin: Mouton de\nGruyter. Sasse, H.J.(1993) \"Das Nomen â eine universelle Kategorie?\"\nin Sprachtypologie und Universalienforschung 46 (3)) Jan Rijkhoff\n(2007) \"Word Classes\" Language and Linguistics Compass 1 (6) , 709â726\nRijkhoff, Jan (2004), \"The Noun Phrase\", Oxford University Press,\nISBN 0-19-926964-5 \n\nThere are six theoretically possible basic word orders for the transitive\nsentence: subjectâverbâobject (SVO), subjectâobjectâverb (SOV),\nverbâsubjectâobject (VSO), verbâobjectâsubject (VOS), objectâsubjectâverb (OSV)\nand objectâverbâsubject (OVS). The overwhelming majority of the world's\nlanguages are either SVO or SOV, with a much smaller but still significant\nportion using VSO word order. The remaining three arrangements are exceptionally\nrare, with VOS being slightly more common than OSV, and OVS being significantly\nmore rare than the two preceding orders. Russel S.Tomlin;1986;Basic word\norder: Functional principles;London:Croom Helm\n","linknr":349,"url":"Word_order","recorded":1374765199,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Word_order&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Word_order&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Linguistic_typology","/wiki/Morphological_typology","/wiki/Isolating_language","/wiki/Synthetic_language","/wiki/Polysynthetic_language","/wiki/Fusional_language","/wiki/Agglutinative_language","/wiki/Morphology_(linguistics)#Paradigms_and_morphosyntax","/wiki/Morphosyntactic_alignment","/wiki/Nominative%E2%80%93accusative_language","/wiki/Ergative%E2%80%93absolutive_language","/wiki/Split_ergativity","/wiki/Austronesian_alignment","/wiki/Active%E2%80%93stative_language","/wiki/Tripartite_language","/wiki/Nominative%E2%80%93absolutive_language","/wiki/Direct%E2%80%93inverse_language","/wiki/Syntactic_pivot","/wiki/Theta_role","/wiki/VO_language","/wiki/Subject%E2%80%93verb%E2%80%93object","/wiki/Verb%E2%80%93su